{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"22b6625b-a0c5-413a-ac47-67d6892ef753","content":"You don't need the SDK. `dotnet-trace` is a standalone global tool you can install or copy in:\n\n**Option 1 — Install as a global tool (requires .NET runtime)**\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$HOME/.dotnet/tools\"\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling\n```\n\n**Option 2 — Download the self-contained single-file build (no runtime needed)**\n```bash\ncurl -sSL https://aka.ms/dotnet-trace/linux-x64 -o dotnet-trace\nchmod +x ./dotnet-trace\n./dotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling\n```\n\nOption 2 is usually best for containers since it's a single binary with no dependencies. Use `--profile cpu-sampling` for high-CPU investigations. The output `.nettrace` file can be copied out and opened in Visual Studio, PerfView, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app).\n\n**Tip:** Find the target PID with `ps aux | grep dotnet` or `pidof dotnet` inside the container.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"96add22c-2f98-4003-b3e9-bcbe3f867153","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to get `dotnet-trace` into a Linux container that doesn't have the .NET SDK installed, to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app experiencing high CPU.\n\nThis is a general knowledge question about .NET diagnostics tooling — I can answer this directly without needing to search any codebase.","outputTokens":369,"requestId":"1B88:34550C:144B161:16D48A4:6A0281DC"},"id":"e1765875-89ef-4593-a8a2-b2b64bea73b7","timestamp":"2026-05-12T01:27:01.720Z","parentId":"490f2e3b-2b3b-4450-be66-d720cceb1318"}
